This each student must do for himself, consulting a good dictionary‚ as editors and editions are not always to be depended on. Here it is the diphthongs that present the chief difficulty and call for the greatest care.

In pronouncing diphthongs sound both vowels, but glide so rapidly from the first to the second as to offer to the ear buta single sound. In the publication of the Cambridge (Eng.) Philological Society on “Pronunciation of Latin in the Augustan Period‚'' the following directions are given:

“The pronunciation of these diphthongs‚ of which the last three are extremely rare, is best learnt by first sounding each vowel separately and then running thern together, ae as ah-eh‚ au as ah-oo‚ oe as o-eh, ei as eh-ee‚ eu as eh-oo‚

and ui as oo-ee.'' Thus :
